name: iter::traits::iterator::Iterator::product

iter::traits::accum::Product::product.doc:
Takes an iterator and generates `Self` from the elements by multiplying
 the items.

src:
fn product

(self) -> P where Self: Sized, P: Product, { Product::product(self) }
doc:
Iterates over the entire iterator, multiplying all the elements

 An empty iterator returns the one value of the type.

 `product()` can be used to multiply any type implementing [`Product`][`core::iter::Product`],
 including [`Option`][`Option::product`] and [`Result`][`Result::product`].

 # Panics

 When calling `product()` and a primitive integer type is being returned,
 method will panic if the computation overflows and overflow checks are
 enabled.

 # Examples

 ```
 fn factorial(n: u32) -> u32 {
     (1..=n).product()
 }
 assert_eq!(factorial(0), 1);
 assert_eq!(factorial(1), 1);
 assert_eq!(factorial(5), 120);
 ```
